  "created": "2025-10-14",
  "description": "The E. coli osmotic stress response is a sophisticated biological system enabling the bacterium to adapt and survive in environments with high external osmolarity. Upon encountering hyperosmotic conditions, E. coli rapidly expels intracellular water, leading to a critical decrease in turgor pressure and cell volume. The immediate compensatory actions involve the activation of mechanosensitive channels (MscL, MscS, MscK) and K+ transporters (TrkA, KdpFABC), facilitating a rapid influx of K+ ions to partially restore cellular turgor. Simultaneously, global regulatory systems, notably RpoS (sigma S) and CosR, are activated to coordinate the transcription of a wide range of osmoprotective genes. The PhoP/PhoQ two-component system also contributes to this general stress adaptation. A crucial long-term strategy is the accumulation of compatible solutes like glycine betaine, proline, and trehalose, either by active transport from the environment or through de novo synthesis pathways. These molecules help balance intracellular osmotic pressure and protect vital macromolecules. Additionally, E. coli increases ubiquinone biosynthesis, which is shown to enhance membrane stability and improve overall osmotic tolerance. These integrated responses collectively lead to the restoration of turgor, maintenance of cell volume, and protection of cellular components, ensuring E. coli's survival and growth under osmotic stress.",
  "id": "ecoli_e._coli_osmotic_stress_response",
